Review: As disappointed in this as I am with Napoleon. It's similar in the sense all the ingredients are there but I'm not just digging it. The racing and the cars are superfluous and the drama just isn't very good. I can't criticise Driver, Cruz or Woodley but I simply don't have a reason to give enough of a shit about Enzo or the ladies. It's a poor script that holds this back, the sound and cinematography is great though.

This is a strange one - it has everything you need for a 5 star banger. Great director, great lead, brilliant score, suitable epic cinematography with the added benefit of the story of Napoleon Bonaparte backing it up. Yet, somehow, this feels empty. Part of the challenge is condensing down his story to a feature length film runtime and in doing so, you rob the ability to maximise character development. The result is that you somehow feel nothing about a…
What am I doing with my life - it's like Gravity and Apollo 13 but shitter in every way

Hot take but this is incredibly mid - unsure why it's got the plaudits it does because aside from Kennedy's great performance, there isn't much here except Paul Newman's blue eyes and that alone does not a good film make.

Ehhhhhhh. It's a less good version of The Big Short. Like Don't Look Up, no change will come of this as long as everyone keeps tolerating this fuckery and there's no signs that's gonna happen anytime soon. This would be 2 stars if it weren't for Paul Dano and Megan Thee Stallion.

Throw the name John Woo at an action aficionado's face and they'll smile - the man behind Face / Off and and Broken Arrow has a certain reputation. The problem is that once you stare at his filmography, you are reminded that his entire body of work is supremely average minus a few glorious high notes and funnily enough, so is Silent Night.Joel Kinnaman plays a guy - Brian? - who loses his son to a random act of…

Ahead of its time when it comes to non-linear time and heist movies. A violent movie for the times and a prototype for movies like Inside Man and Oceans 11. While it's not nearly as well known as Kubrick's other films, you can see the writing and the talent with the ability to maximise everything available to him, even if the resources and budget aren't there. Superbly paced as well!You forget how clear dialogue used to be in movies…

Honestly...first 2 acts don't have enough to get you hooked and the format sucks. Watch The Sting if you want a good movie about this sort of thing because it has better writing, performances and you actually give a shit about the characters.

Honestly this is fun as fuck. Really smartly done with layers that kids will appreciate and an underlying message around feminism that anyone who actually thinks about it will get. Gosling is SO good as Ken but the star of the show is Robbie, in fact the whole cast does a stellar job.

The good - some of the tidbits that are from the game such as the racing overlays, random sound effects. The driving scenes are good, I dig the fact it didn't lean too heavily into the story side of things. Also managed to perfectly capture what a out of touch with his son father sounds like.
